The article reflects on the legacy of Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. and the continued struggle for racial equality in America. The author recounts their visit to the National Civil Rights Museum in Memphis, where Dr. King was assassinated, and describes the atmosphere of his preserved room. They emphasize the importance of fulfilling the promise of America for all citizens and acknowledge the progress made in addressing racial equity, but also recognize the ongoing challenges in achieving racial justice, protecting voting rights, and combating hate. The article concludes with a call to honor Dr. King's memory by redoubling efforts to deliver his vision of a just and equal America.